"You have saved two lives, sir," he said, with a singular nobility of tone;
                  "thanks, thanks! And now, my child," he added, turning to Cannie, "go change your
                  dress, or you will be ill."

"I have heard that Mr. Addison and Mr. Steele wrote together," said Miss Argal;
                  "can your lordship tell me which of them wrote this? It is so elegantly
                  composed—so delightful!"

"And where were you?" thundered the youth, in a tone which made the servant quake;
                  "cowardly wretch! Why are you alive, to speak to me—when your mistress is a
                  prisoner of the Indians?"

"What have you done with my child?" cried the old man, flushing to the temples,
                  and speaking in a tone of such terrible anguish that it made the hearers tremble;
                  "where is my child? Bring her hither!"
